How could you be so callous? Think about others for a change. Think about the families of the people who took their lives there and how it makes them feel to see this Hollywood shit show.   Please go watch the actual documentary on this forest, instead of this "horror movie".  Maybe it will give you some insight on how serious this issue really is. And you would be able to see how these people really spend their last days in this forest alone.

text: To everyone saying that people complaining about this being in poor taste are too sensitive: no, they are not too sensitive.  Having lost my sister to suicide, I can say that this movie is completely disrespectful. It is glorifying, exploiting and romanticizing the act of suicide. Suicide is not some mysterious, intriguing enigma that qualifies it as something to be portrayed as magical and appealing. It is a tragedy that should not be used to further Hollywood's success. This film is disrespectful to all those who have gone to the forest in desperation and all those families who have suffered from the loss and whose lives have been irrevocably changed.

People are boycotting it because of accusations made before the movie even came out - I say that everyone should go see it just to prove that we wont tolerate that kind of bs. text: From some bleeding-heart tosser that you don't want to hear from: people routinely go into this forest to hang themselves. There are signs early into the forest saying "there is hope" and "seek help" and such and such. For a legitimate view, there's a VICE documentary about it where some guy (Japanese) ventures in and tries to persuade people to NOT die and return to civilisation.  I've been-there-done-that and I - and so does my family - have the scars to prove it.  No-one who dies in that way is going to have enough venom to attack random strangers. To make a straight-to-video horror movie out of this subject is, as a person who has broached this subject via a serious illness, filthy and gross. I should just calm down and get over it; just a bunch of dudes with a *lightbulb!* idea who decided to make a silly horror movie.  But there are literally skeletons wreathed in rotting clothing still hanging from trees in that place. They are not going to grab you and drag you underground. They need to be respected and so do their families, not prostituted into another garden-variety, opportunist American film below F-grade that thought "oh wait - this is a good idea!".  So might be a good film if you enjoyed the first Evil Dead. Otherwise, sorry bros, please choose some different subject matter. There are films about Nazi soldiers coming back to life just for shits and giggles. No horror films about the camps themselves. There are documentaries about notable suicide "hotspots' - no horror films about them.  This is annoying to a lot of "oh whatever" morons but seriously, fuck the premise of this film and those that thought it would be a REMOTELY decent thing to shoot. It is just the perfect example of Western (forgive my categories,  but they stand) interpretation and then perverse disfigurement of someone else; culture.  ~~~  TL:DR:--  This place in Japan is a forest where people either go to kill themselves, or to look at the bodies of people who have killed themselves. It is a very sad and sacred place. To make a horror film about it - the poor sods that died in *that* way coming back to hurt others - is just fucking stupidly, ungodly, barbarically, ludicrously wrong and ridiculous. It makes me want to slam my head into a wall in the vain hope that I might make it through. But hey. Money!
